Patch Set 1:Urk - using virtual inheritance for all of the OutputDevice ref and unref calls ... like this:class VCL_DLLPUBLIC OutputDevice : public virtual VclReferenceBaseI assume that this will then put all those nice previously in-lined, and optimize-able out mnRefCnt++ and -- pairs behind virtual function calls. But of course - we could look at the generated code to see if it in fact it is that awful ;-)What's the stripped binary size increase would be a good question.

Patch Set 3:Without looking too deeply, this smells like it might be breaking the implementation of the WebDAV content's "getPropertyValues" command for the sake of broken clients?  offapi/com/sun/star/ucb/Content.idl documents "getPropertyValues" as follows: "The execution will not be aborted, if there are properties requested, that are unknown to the content. The returned row object must contain a NULL value in the corresponding column instead."  (See css.sdbc.XRow.wasNull for how client code is supposed to check for such a "NULL value".)

Patch Set 5:it looks like we still owe you some answers to your questions :)the only way to build with python 2 is to use --enable-python=system and set PYTHON, PYTHON_CFLAGS and PYTHON_LIBS variables manually to the right values, i.e. PYTHON_CFLAGS=`pkg-config --cflags python` PYTHON_LIBS=`pkg-config --libs python` before running autogen.sh(this is deliberately inconvenient so that newbies don't do it by accident)the only easy way to run all python tests is "make check" but that will run all tests, the faster way is to run every PythonTest_foo that exists manually via "make PythonTest_foo".unfortunately it often happens that broken commits are pushed to master and that will break your jenkins build here too if your change is based on the broken master, probably that's what happened here in some cases.

Patch Set 5:> Just curious, what's the benefit of genLang, compared to the > current l10ntools, after the kill-sdf branch was merged? >  > See http://libreoffice.hu/2012/11/27/featurekillsdf-branch-merged/ > for the background.the kill sdf was a very good thing, but it did not change the tools or the method. The "save" method in the old tools was rewritten to save .pot files.genLang "reinvents" the tools in a C++ fashion, making it more maintainable. You can however argue, that since the old tools work, why change it. The best reason for that is to move away from the central "make translations" that runs find over the source tree, and into adding the files to the local makefiles (e.g. define ui files like you define cxx files).

Patch Set 4:> > RGB happens to be defined by wingdi.h and leaks from multiple > > places. This was the easiest/simplest fix; to undef it where it > > conflicts. For other cases it was enough to undef them in > postwin.h > > and make sure it's called after including windows headers. >  > But wouldn't it be better to handle undef'ing RGB in postwin.h, and > make sure any include of wingdi.h is wrapped in prewin/postwin.h? I tried that. And can give it another try. But it would require a much bigger change, obviously. The main problem is that wingdi.h is actually included from other windows headers too. So we can't fully control when it's included. But can give it another shot and narrow it down further. In fact, I spent hours trying to find what file includes the conflicting values to create this patch. > The current fix allows workdir/CustomTarget/officecfg/registry/officecfg/Office/Common.hxx > to be included, but if a source file happens to first include that > officecfg/Office/Common.hxx, then include wingdi.h, and later wants > to acutally use the struct RGB from Common.hxx, it still runs into > a problem.Well, that would be be a problem _only_ if wingdi.h was already included _before_ Office/Common.h, and in that case the build would fail because the macro would conflict with the declaration of RGB (my patch avoids this situation).However, if wingdi.h was _not_ included at the point of #undef RGB, then nothing bad would happen if it is included afterwards. Unless I missed something, I don't see how there would still be a problem, as wingdi.h will define RGB without issue.I should add that I hated this particular line of my patch. I share your view that it's best avoided altogether. But I couldn't find a better solution. Will try again though.

Patch Set 1:To elaborate on how to amend a patch: The trick here is preserving the same Change-Id of the commit message, so that Gerrit recognizes it should be on the same thread. Locally, you do a new commit, then you do `git rebase -i HEAD~2' to squash that with the previous commit. Then you push and Gerrit will detect your updated squashed commit as a new version (or ÔÇ£patch setÔÇØ) without creating a new thread. Hope this helps!

Patch Set 1:> To elaborate on how to amend a patch: The trick here is preserving > the same Change-Id of the commit message, so that Gerrit recognizes > it should be on the same thread. Locally, you do a new commit, then > you do `git rebase -i HEAD~2' to squash that with the previous > commit.Git commit --amend is a much easier way to do that.iow checkout your gerrit patchdo the modificationscommit them using --amendgit push origin HEAD:refs/for/master Then you push and Gerrit will detect your updated squashed > commit as a new version (or ÔÇ£patch setÔÇØ) without creating a new > thread. Hope this helps!

Patch Set 3:Replying to myself: Yeah, they are.USING_X11 is TRUE when we are building for a platform that uses X11, and we haven't used the --without-x option. with_x is "no" when we have used the switch --without-x (which used to be called --enable-headless), and that de facto has been developed only for platforms where X11 *could* be used. So USING_X11!=TRUE turns out to be equivalent to with_x==no. Unless I miss something;)In theory one could also imagine building a LibreOffice for Windows or OS X that would not use any display-oriented APIs, but that would be fairly pointless, as that functionality is always present in the OS anyway. It isn't like Linux, where some people think it is useful to have installations without any X11 stuff.

Patch Set 6:I checked the run-time behavior and it works very well.  And I checked the ODF attribute name, and I *think* that, although there are several other names we could re-use for this purpose, repeat-item-labels is probably reasonable.Now, 2 things remain.  One is that we need a new unit test to cover this new feature.  Hopefully you can pick one of the existing test cases in ucalc_pivottable.cxx as a model and add a new test case. I *think* you can use either XML_NP_CALC_EXT or XML_NP_LO_EXT for this.  Eike, do you have any advice on which namespace to use?That's all I have to say on this.  Great work!

Patch Set 3:When designing the framework, we had two basic ideas:- interesting document models are easier to be loaded from some format, than building them from code- checking an in-memory document model is reasonably easy (usually by using the UNO API), at least easier than asserting a written file (think of manually checking a binary .doc result)That's why for export tests, we do an import->export->import sequence. That ensures that the doc. models can be still stored in a file, allows asserting the result using the UNO API, and still export problems are detected. (I'm just re-stating what's in sw/qa/extras/README, just in case for some reason that file is not clear.) Hopefully this makes it clear how export tests are done. :-)Regarding loosing data during import/export: sure, sometimes that's necessary when e.g. our numbering types and MSO's numbering types do not match. In your case, the provided tests passed just fine when also the exporter got included in the chain, that's why I changed that. As long as it passes, it's safe to change, and it ensures that your export improvements won't break in the future silently. ;-)

Patch Set 1:removing commented sections is usually rather safe -- cherry-picking is somewhat robust against that. For blank lines, there is no convention on how many we should have were, so this might easily lead to a fight over that (and we shouldnt bother with that then). Patch Set 1:This change is related to columns in text sections, not columns for pages. I guess page columns are not exported to HTML because there is really no generally applicable way of doing that; HTML pages do not have fixed height like pages in Writer do.To test this you need to- Open a new empty Writer document- Choose Insert -> Section- Go to Columns tab and type in a number, 3 for example, click Insert.- now you can see the little grey section markers, paste some long text inside those.- save as HTML, you should end up with a HTML document that has a MULTICOL element that contains the column count both in the old non-standard COLS-attribute and in the new css column-count attribute.PS. I hope this is the right way to respond to the review comment. I'm just trying to learn how to use this Gerrit tool.

Patch Set 1:"The whole check appears to be rather pointless. Do we actually use the result anywhere?"While we don't appear to be using HAVE_BOOST_UNORDERED_MAP anywhere (so setting it could be removed), we do #include "boost/unordered_map.hxx" in lots of places.  So if the system boost does not support that, we should probably error-out/switch to our boost.Forcing -std=gnu++0x for the check without coordinating that with HAVE_CXX0X (which will determine whether --std=gnu++0x is actually enabled in the build) is not really helpful, though.

Patch Set 1:Also system boost supports it, there is no reason why it should not do so.You only have to use the header with the standard enabled in cxxflags, and if you don't it warns on you like this:                 from /usr/include/boost/unordered_map.hpp:16,                 from conftest.cpp:69:/usr/lib/gcc/x86_64-pc-linux-gnu/4.6.3/include/g++-v4/bits/c++0x_warning.h:32:2: error: #error This file requires compiler and library support for the upcoming ISO C++ standard, C++0x. This support is currently experimental, and must be enabled with the -std=c++0x or -std=gnu++0x compiler options.

Patch Set 1:Wrt. the starvation - actually that was due to the logging; we have so much debugging stuff that it was blocking considerably when writing to the console, making the queue grow.  Without that, all works fine even with the unmodified TileQueue :-)But I worked on the TileQueue too - it seems unnecessary to do all the priority shuffling when inserting, when the prioritization changes with every view switch, and instead do it only when the tile is requested - which seems to work nicely.Wrt. an own queue for tiles - that is exactly the thing that makes the synchronzation hard, as then it is necessary to synchronize between those 2 queues; which in turn kills all the advantage of 2 queues :-)Wrt. PNG compression; if we want to thread it, then let's thread just the compression - that'll make it local, more maintainable, and we can go with as many threads there as we wish (for just the PNG compression piece of code).Wrt. the 342125b8ea - thanks for that!  Unfortunately that again just adds code :-(Either way, please check https://cgit.freedesktop.org/libreoffice/online/log/?h=private/kendy/tilesandcallbacks , I'd really like to get that in...  I've tested it with several people in a session, and it performed pretty well thanks to all your work I was able to build on.

Patch Set 2:To summarize what has been discussed on IRC today:I'm not a big fan of encouraging users to use deprecated and insecure protocols (let's be honest, DDE *is* deprecated and insecure). If this is mainly about inserting links with relative paths, maybe your goals could be achieved by using relative references, i.e. =DDE("soffice"; "some/relative/path"; "SheetX.CellY")would become ='some/relative/path'#SheetXCellY'and the development effort could be targeted at implementing some UI and clipboard support for relative references and fixing outstanding relative reference issues (sometimes target doc doesn't update if source doc changes, ~/ path doesn't expand correctly etc.)

Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1> > Why would you want to link all these libraries into libmerged? > The hope is to start faster. e.g. if it runs as conversion server.And does it help?The point of libmerged was to merge libraries which are always loaded on start.You can get them with something like similar script:for app in 'writer' 'calc' 'draw' 'impress' 'base'do    LD_DEBUG=files OOO_EXIT_POST_STARTUP=1 ./instdir/program/soffice "--${app}" 2> temp_${app}.txt    cat temp_${app}.txt  | grep "calling init"  | cut -f 2 | cut -d " " -f 3 | sort  | uniq > libs_${app}.txtdonecat libs_* | sort | grep home | uniq -c | sort -r > libraries.txtFrom these, only acc should be merged.If it really will be useful for some scenario,maybe try resurrecting --enable-mergelibs=allor somehow enable to define specific set of libs on configure or...(See also fa8aaaadc38372185d6d29d8d91391907e95b689)

Patch Set 1:Hmm, is this only a nice-to-have patch or it makes life really hard on the g-d side if this is not accepted?I'm asking as up to today, we could freely add as many new signals as we wanted to the widget without breaking ABI. However, with your patch, the list of signals become part of the ABI and we limit the number of new signals ever to be added.In other words it's a large cost to support these function pointers -- if possible, it would be really nice to avoid this. The larger the interface we promise to be stable, the harder to make future changes.

Patch Set 2:@tml:Yes, The GCD() function is Calc matches the Excel function, with two notes:-Excel has limits for the size of the arguments (must be less than 2E53), Calc doesn't and never had that limit (neither Calc's own, nor add-in function);-Excel GCD accepts only integer arguments in Excel versions prior to 2007 and accepts floating point arguments since Excel 2007, Calc accepts all numeric arguments (both Calc's own as add-in function).It is quite common for Calc functions to be more tolerant with respect to type and/or numeric value limits than their Excel counterparts.

Patch Set 6:I still don't like introducing a new document-wide UNO setting when we already have a setting in ODF format doing exactly the same ...Anyway, I did some git archaeology and found out that this "Impress always opens on 1st slide" is an artificial restriction imposed by a design document + OOo feature request from 2005 (https://bz.apache.org/ooo/show_bug.cgi?id=50902)Moreover, keyboard accelerator listed therein (Shift-F5) that was supposed to be used to jump to the last edited slide (the one saved as SelectedPage) no longer works, since it is used for different purpose now (start a slideshow from current slide)So I think this restriction (always open on 1st slide, unless the presentation is an embedded OLE object) can nowadays be removed and that should be the way to fix this issue. I.e. removing this 'if ...( SFX_CREATE_MODE_EMBEDDED == pDoc->GetDocSh()->GetCreateMode()' condition when reading SelectedPage setting ... unless it crashes Impress or cause other nasties ...Anyway, I'm adding Thorsten to Cc: to get a second opinion on that ...

(pDrawDoc->GetCurrentPage() )Can you please cherry-pick and try. I don't think we need that import and export code as mentioned in comment 3 on the bug page.Thanks for the letting me know about the variable naming, will fix that.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2Actually this is not exactly a duplicate.Calc has 2 separate "paste special" dialogs. One is when pasting from system clipboard, and the other is pasting from Calc itself.  This one you are proposing to change is used for the 2nd variant.Try opening a new Calc document, and while nothing is copied, hit Ctrl-Shift-V.  This will bring up the system paste special dialog.  Now, select some cells and Ctrl-C to copy, then Ctrl-Shift-V. This will bring up the Calc paste special dialog.I'm not saying we shouldn't change this wording, but I'm not in favor of calling this "insert contents" which would make less sense than "paste special".
